  "prompt": "How do you write a six line poem?",
  "response": "Writing a six-line poem, also known as a *sestet*, can be a fun and creative exercise. Here's a step-by-step guide to crafting one:\n\n1. **Choose a Theme or Idea**: Decide what your poem will be about\u2014love, nature, a memory, an emotion, etc.\n\n2. **Consider the Tone**: Will it be serious, playful, reflective, or something else? The tone will guide your word choice.\n\n3. **Experiment with Form**:\n   - You can write in free verse (no specific rhyme or meter).\n   - Or use a structured form like *sestina*, *hexastich*, or a rhyming pattern (e.g., AABBCC, ABABCC).\n\n4. **Focus on Imagery and Language**: Use vivid descriptions, metaphors, or sensory details to bring your poem to life.\n\n5. **Keep it Concise**: Since it\u2019s only six lines, every word should carry weight.\n\n6. **Edit and Refine**: Read your poem aloud to check for rhythm and clarity. Make adjustments as needed.\n\nHere\u2019s an example of a six-line poem:\n\n---\n\nThe moon hums softly,  \na lullaby for the night.  \nStars trace their stories  \nacross the velvet sky.  \nThe world holds its breath,  \nwaiting for dawn's reply.  \n\n---\n\nLet me know if you'd like help crafting one!",
